","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1146":"1146","1244":"1244","before 1172":"before 1172","Ermington, Devon, England":"Ermington, Devon, England","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Newton-Peverell, Wimborne, Dorset, England":"Wimborne, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","South Stoneham, Hampshire, England":"South Stoneham, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mainsbridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Mansbridge in South Stoneham (Hants)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":43,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":52,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Mainsbridge was born in 1172, in South Stoneham, Hampshire, England as the daughter of Thomas de Mainsbridge and wife Thomas de Mainsbridge. She married William de Peverell III about 1190, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1244, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1172–1244":"1172–1244","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1190–1237":"1190–1237","1198–1223":"1198–1223","1205–1273":"1205–1273","1146–1217":"1146–1217","–Female":"Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1198":"1198","1273":"1273","1172":"1172","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1146":"1146","1244":"1244","before 1172":"enne 1172","Ermington, Devon, England":"Ermington, Devon, England","Somerset, England":"Somers